etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in John Trevisa (c1342–?1402), translator. From outbreak + -ing

definitions: An outburst or eruption; an emergence from latency; a lapse from moral conduct; an unruly or violent misdemeanour.

etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in Samuel Daniel (?1563–1619), poet and historian. From outbreak + -ing

definitions: Breaking or bursting out, erupting; departing or lapsing from moral or religious rectitude.
